  🤔 About the benefits of Since a few years now, we started to design various  for internal batch usage, on our Java Stack on top of  and , delivered as images, and run on .Avoid as much as possible to write unnecessary documentations : each tool should describe himself according to a common patternRely on the best possible practicesAnd overall : deliver a consistent first-class UX to OPSTherefore I started to read and follow the following site to follow the best possible guidelines : An open-source guide to help you write better command-line programs, taking traditional UNIX principles and updating them for the modern day.This is the source code for the guide. To read it, go to clig.dev.The content of the guide lives in a single Markdown file, content/_index.md.
The website is built using Hugo.To run Hugo locally to see your changes, run:$ brew install hugo
$ cd <path>/<to>/cli-guidelines/
$ hugo server
To view the site on an external mobile device, run:hugo server --bind 0.0.0.0 --baseURL http://$(hostname -f):1313
On my very own side I gave a try during a hackathon to Go and  : Then, I wanted to bring my team to the Go experience at the office  as sometimes we need to deliver apps to systems on which we don't want or can't install new softwares : so delivering a static binary thanks to Go and  seemed a good option for effortless cross-compilation... and of course build the best possible  thanks to Cobra.So I used this opportunity to sharpen our skill with my team : 

